description._content:
The Hobart Building (right), at 582-592 Market Street, was built in 1914 by Willis Polk.  Completed in only eleven months, it was the tallest in San Francisco upon completion.  The 21-floor Beaux Arts tower with renaissance/baroque ornamentation was said to be Polk's favorite of all the building he designed in the years following the 1906 Earthquake.  Shaped to fit its asymmetric polygonal site, the building's bare flank was exposed when a neighboring structure was torn down.

44 Montgomery (left), is a 43-story story built in 1966-67 by John Graham and Associates as the headquarters for Wells Fargo Bank.  At its completion, it was the tallest building west of the Mississippi.

description._content:
Native Sons' Monument, also known as Admission Day, designed by sculptor Douglas Tilden and architect Willis Polk, was dedicated on Market Street on September 5, 1897.  It was moved to Golden Gate Park in 1948 and returned to Market and Montgomery in 1977.  The monument depicts a larger-than-life size female figure of an angel atop a granite shaft holds aloft a book inscribed with the date of California's entry into the union (September 8, 1850). The angel stands erect with her arms held straight above her head, holding the book with both hands. At the shaft's base, a young miner, pick on shoulder, armed with a six-shooter, waves an American flag.

The Hobart Building (right), at 582-592 Market Street, was built in 1914 by Willis Polk.  Completed in only eleven months, it was the tallest in San Francisco upon completion.  The 21-floor Beaux Arts tower with renaissance/baroque ornamentation was said to be Polk's favorite of all the building he designed in the years following the 1906 Earthquake.  Shaped to fit its asymmetric polygonal site, the building's bare flank was exposed when a neighboring structure was torn down.

44 Montgomery (left), is a 43-story story built in 1966-67 by John Graham and Associates as the headquarters for Wells Fargo Bank.  At its completion, it was the tallest building west of the Mississippi.

description._content:
Hobart Building: Willis Polk, 1914

Willis Polk designed the base and pole in 1908 for United Railways' trolley poles with street lights. The City required the company to provide highly ornamental poles, with lamps and electricity, as the price of permitting the much opposed overhead trolley wires. 

The tops were designed in 1916 by sculptor Leo Lentelli and engineer Walter D'Arcy Ryan, whose lighting designs for the Panama Pacific International Exposition of 1915 had inspired emulation on the City's principal thoroughfare. 

This project was linked to graft payments to Mayor Schmitz, political boss Abe Ruef, and seventeen of the eighteen members of the Board of Supervisors.

description._content: built 1909-1911 decorations and remodeling by Julia Morgan, 1938 "Phoebe Apperson Hearst commissioned the New York architectural firm of Kirby, Petit & Green to design the new structure. The initial thought was to construct a grand 26 story building topped with a 1-story copper lantern balcony on a roof of copper tiles covered in gold flecke. Inside the lantern would be a chiming clock. The City decided to implement a coordinated height plan along the Market Street corridor in the aftermath of the near total destruction of the buildings and ruled that the Hearst Building could be no taller than 12 stories above the ground floor." building website- As constructed, it is a scaled-down version of the original design; That design had called for a larger structure with an elaborate upper zone that recalled Schweinfurth's pre 1906 building, to be surmounted by a colossal, overscaled clock tower. As built, it is a two-part vertical composition with differentiated end bays. The building has three facades, given vertical emphasis by the pier and window system. The ground level and mezzanine have polychrome terra cotta work. The elaborate entry hood has a broken segmental pediment and a medallion insert with the initial "H". Intricate metal screen with an animal motif is used between the Corinthian pilasters. The white terra cotta piers contrast well with the dark brown vertical window shafts. The cornice is elaborated with the same polychrome terra cotta scheme as the base: fruit-like ornament with anthemion antefixae. This is the only one of the three newspaper buildings at this corner which still functions as newspaper offices. The angled corner of the facade follows the lot lines and helps give definition to "newspaper angle", once the heart of the city. San Francisco Property Information Map In 1938, famed architect Julia Morgan was retained by (William Randolph) Hearst to complete a remodel of the Hearst Building’s exterior entry way, the lobby on the ground floor and the parapet roof structure. Her work included the installation of a field of 20 cast bronze medallions containing fanciful animals above the front door, the addition of patriotic red white & blue lighting around the medallions, a crest above the front entry, an elaborate and beautiful lobby interior and updated elevator interiors. Her work remains unchanged today and is visible to the passerby. - building website 691 Market Street, San Francisco 2014-July-D 063

description._content: The Hobart Building is an office high rise located at 582–592 Market Street and Montgomery Street in the financial district of San Francisco. It was completed in 1914 after only eleven months, which led to accusations that it had been constructed with a degree of recklessness, and was at the time the second tallest building in the city, with 21 floors, and 87 m (285 ft). Said to be the favorite commercial building of its designer, Willis Polk, its sculpted terra cotta exterior with Baroque ornamentation, and handcrafted brass and Italian marble interior are a noted example of neoclassicist architecture. Its unusual shape was dictated by the site, which was an asymmetric polygon, and since a neighboring structure was torn down, exposing one flank, it is now even more idiosyncratic and striking.- wikipedia P1100532

description._content:
Crocker Galleria Roof Terrace on the San Francisco Architecture Tour.  San Francisco has a number of Privately Owned Public Open Spaces (POPOS) that were created through a lot of complicated zoning laws. Their laws have things involving air rights that limit the height of buildings but can be sold. If your building has 5 floors but air rights for 15, you can sell the rights for the 10 so a taller building can be built on that block. Much like valuable water rights in the dry parts of the West. Find out the details on the great Architecture Walking Tour.

In the background is the Hobart Building. "Completed in 1914 by the famed architect Willis Polk, and approaching its 100-year anniversary, the Hobart Building is considered one of San Francisco’s most well-known historical landmarks. From the sculpted terra cotta exterior to the handcrafted brass and Italian marble interior, the Hobart Building is a stunning example of classical revival architecture."

description._content:
Explore #325
Nov. 24, 2009

The Hobart Building is not one of San Francisco's tallest buildings (the 7th smallest actually) but it is one of the oldest and is often credited as being one of San Francisco's classic highrises.  The building was completed in 1914 and was designed by architect Willis Polk and the building features impressive steel masonry as well as its terra cotta exterior and baroque shape.  Frankly, it was one of the coolest buildings I have seen in a downtown city and for me it really epitomized my feeling of what old downtown San Francisco would have been like.  The sun was shining so fantastic on this day and I was lucky to have the light catch this building just perfect, not washing it out, but instead accenting its beautiful features as well as painting it.  This image was captured in July 2009 with my Nikon D90.  Enjoy!

description._content: The Hobart Building, at 582-592 Market Street, was built in 1914 by Willis Polk.  Completed in only eleven months, it was the tallest in San Francisco upon completion.  The 21-floor Beaux Arts tower with renaissance/baroque ornamentation was said to be Polk's favorite of all the building he designed in the years following the 1906 Earthquake.  Shaped to fit its asymmetric polygonal site, the building's bare flank was exposed when a neighboring structure was torn down.
